{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An AI Executive Steering Committee (ESC) is the senior governance body that owns enterprise AI strategy, prioritizes the portfolio, and resolves issues that operating teams cannot handle independently. It convenes regularly to review program health, approve major investment shifts, set policy guardrails, and maintain executive alignment. The committee occupies the highest rung of AI governance below the board itself and is the organizational embodiment of executive sponsorship."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "AI initiatives fail most often not because of technology but because of organizational fragmentation. Without a standing body with real authority, strategic conflicts between business units go unresolved, risk posture is inconsistent, and funding decisions lag months behind need. An ESC cuts through these dynamics by giving AI a permanent seat at the leadership table and creating a predictable rhythm for decisions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At the enterprise scale, agentic AI systems touch data, process, and people across many functions simultaneously. The ESC provides the cross-functional legitimacy—and the accountable signatures—needed to authorize these wide-surface deployments and hold owners accountable for outcomes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Benefits"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Reduces time-to-decision for cross-functional AI issues from weeks to days"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Creates a single source of truth for strategic AI priorities and investment allocation"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prevents siloed initiatives that duplicate capability or create conflicting risk posture"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Gives external regulators and auditors a named governance entity to engage"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Accelerates adoption by resolving organizational resistance at the executive level"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Provides program teams with visible top-cover, enabling faster change management"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs and limitations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Committees can become bottlenecks if operating rhythm is too slow or quorum requirements are strict"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Without clear decision rights, ESC sessions devolve into status updates rather than decisions"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Membership breadth needed for legitimacy can dilute the focus needed for speed"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Executives may delegate attendance to deputies who lack authority, undermining effectiveness"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "ESC authority must be chartered formally; informal steering groups lack enforcement power"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The ESC operates through a tiered governance model. The full committee meets monthly to review portfolio health, approve budget reallocations, and decide on policy updates. Three permanent working groups—Strategy & Prioritization, Risk & Compliance, and Delivery & Architecture—meet weekly and bring recommendation packages to the monthly session. The executive sponsor (typically the CEO or COO) chairs or co-chairs quarterly deep-dives that review long-horizon strategy and organizational performance against targets."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each working group has a named lead, a defined scope, and a standing decision-log. Items that fall within a working group's scope are decided there; items that require cross-cutting authority or budget above a threshold are escalated to the full committee. The escalation ladder and threshold amounts are written into the ESC charter at formation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The monthly packet distributed 72 hours before the meeting includes: portfolio dashboard, open issues with recommendation, budget variance, risk register delta, and upcoming key milestones. Decisions are recorded in a shared decision log accessible to program teams the day after the meeting."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "AI Steering Committee governance hierarchy showing Executive Sponsor, Steering Committee members, three working groups, and governance cadence"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The diagram shows the three-tier structure: a single executive sponsor at the top, the full cross-functional steering committee below, and three permanently chartered working groups that feed it. Governance cadence is layered—weekly at working-group level, monthly at committee level, quarterly at sponsor level."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use it"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "At organization formation of an enterprise AI program (before the first major deployment)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When merging several independent AI teams into a federated capability model"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When escalated regulatory scrutiny demands named accountability at the executive level"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When recurring cross-unit conflicts over data access, priority, or budget stall progress"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When the board or external stakeholders request a governance attestation for AI"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How to implement"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Draft the ESC charter: mission statement, decision rights, membership criteria, quorum rules, charter duration, and amendment process"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Identify and secure commitment from permanent members: CDO, CTO, CFO, CISO, CPO, and two to three domain VP representatives on a rotating basis"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Appoint an ESC program coordinator (usually from the AI Center of Excellence) to own logistics, packet preparation, and decision-log maintenance"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Charter the three working groups, assign leads, and set their scope boundaries and escalation thresholds"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Run an inaugural session to ratify the charter, baseline the portfolio, and agree on the first-quarter priorities"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Establish the recurring calendar, decision-log tool, and communication cadence for distributing outcomes to program teams"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Review the ESC charter annually or after major organizational change to keep membership and authority current"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Examples"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "text"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# ESC Charter excerpt — Decision Rights Matrix\n\nDecision Type                    | Working Group | Steering Committee | Exec Sponsor\n---------------------------------|---------------|--------------------|-------------\nApprove new use-case addition    | Recommend     | Approve (< $500K)  | Approve (> $500K)\nChange portfolio tier of a use case | Recommend  | Approve            | Inform\nSuspend or sunset an initiative  | Recommend     | Approve            | Inform\nApprove new AI vendor/partner    | Assess risk   | Approve            | Inform (> $1M)\nAdopt new AI policy or standard  | Draft         | Approve            | Ratify\nRespond to regulator inquiry     | Prepare docs  | Approve response   | Sign off\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "text"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Sample monthly ESC packet structure\n\n1. Executive Summary (1 page)\n   - Portfolio health: RAG status for all active initiatives\n   - Three decisions required this session\n   - One emerging risk requiring awareness\n\n2. Portfolio Dashboard\n   - Initiative: status, spend YTD, forecast, milestone delta, owner\n\n3. Open Issues for Decision (one page each)\n   - Issue description | Options | Recommendation | Asking for: [Approve / Reject / Defer]\n\n4. Risk Register Delta\n   - New risks added since last meeting\n   - Closed risks\n   - Risk items approaching trigger threshold\n\n5. Budget Variance Report\n   - Actuals vs plan by initiative\n   - Requests to reallocate\n\n6. Key Milestones — Next 60 Days\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Lightweight ESC decision-log entry schema (stored in shared governance tool)\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom datetime import date\nfrom typing import Literal\n\n@dataclass\nclass ESCDecision:\n    decision_id: str                    # ESC-2025-047\n    date: date\n    topic: str                          # Short description\n    decision: Literal[\"Approved\", \"Rejected\", \"Deferred\", \"Tabled\"]\n    rationale: str\n    owner: str                          # Who executes\n    due_date: date | None = None        # If action required\n    dependencies: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)  # IDs of related decisions\n\n# Usage: logged after each session, published to AI program SharePoint within 24h\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# ESC health metrics — tracked monthly by program coordinator\n\nesc_metrics = {\n    \"decisions_made\": 5,            # Target: 3–7 per session\n    \"items_deferred\": 1,            # Target: <= 1; high deferral = insufficient prep\n    \"escalation_rate\": 0.22,        # Working group items escalated to full committee\n                                    # Target: < 0.25\n    \"packet_on_time\": True,         # Distributed >= 72h before meeting\n    \"principal_attendance\": 0.85,   # Named member (not deputy) attendance rate\n                                    # Target: >= 0.80\n    \"decision_log_published_hours\": 18,  # Hours after meeting; Target: <= 24\n}\n\ndef esc_health_rag(metrics: dict) -> str:\n    issues = []\n    if metrics[\"decisions_made\"] < 3:\n        issues.append(\"Low decision volume — agenda may be too light\")\n    if metrics[\"escalation_rate\"] > 0.25:\n        issues.append(\"High escalation rate — working group thresholds too low\")\n    if metrics[\"principal_attendance\"] < 0.80:\n        issues.append(\"Low principal attendance — deputy decisions lack authority\")\n    if metrics[\"decision_log_published_hours\"] > 24:\n        issues.append(\"Decision log delay — program teams waiting for direction\")\n    return \"RED\" if len(issues) >= 2 else \"AMBER\" if issues else \"GREEN\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real-world example"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A large financial services firm launching an agentic customer-service platform formed its ESC eight months before production deployment. Initial membership included the CIO (chair), CDO, Chief Compliance Officer, Head of Retail Banking, Head of Technology Risk, and the CFO's delegate. The committee met monthly with a strict 90-minute agenda using a pre-circulated decision packet."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In the first six months, the ESC made 23 formal decisions: approving four new use cases, sunsetting two pilots that failed their kill criteria, approving a $2.1M budget reallocation from infrastructure to model fine-tuning, and adopting a new human-oversight policy after a near-miss in testing. The working group structure meant that 80 percent of these decisions arrived at the monthly session with full analysis and a recommendation—average decision time dropped from 6.3 weeks (pre-ESC) to 9 days."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Forming the committee without a formal charter—leading to ambiguous authority and contested decisions"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Stacking membership with too many deputies who attend on behalf of principals, reducing decision authority"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Running ESC sessions as status reviews rather than decision forums—no decisions, no value"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Failing to publish the decision log within 24 hours, causing program teams to act on rumor or wait for clarity"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Setting meeting cadence too infrequently (quarterly only) so urgent issues wait too long for resolution"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leaving the ESC in place beyond its charter term without renewal, allowing membership and scope to drift"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Publish decision rights in the charter as a table—ambiguity is the primary cause of ESC dysfunction"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Require the ESC program coordinator to gate-keep the packet: only items that need a decision go in"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use traffic-light (RAG) dashboards rather than narrative status to keep exec attention on exceptions"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rotate one domain VP seat every six months to broaden buy-in without growing the committee"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Record every decision with the explicit rationale and the vote or consensus method; this becomes audit evidence"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Conduct a 30-minute ESC health retrospective quarterly to tune cadence, membership, and process"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Performance and scalability"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An ESC in a large enterprise may govern 30 or more concurrent AI initiatives. As scale increases, the working groups do the heavy lifting: they triage, pre-decide, and only escalate. The monthly committee session should handle no more than five decision items; if consistently higher, the escalation thresholds are too low. Program coordinators track the ratio of items escalated versus decided within working groups as a health metric—target is less than 25 percent escalation rate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For multi-geography enterprises, ESCs sometimes operate with regional sub-committees that handle locally scoped decisions and escalate global questions upward. The charter must define which issues are global versus regional to prevent overlap and gaps."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tooling and ecosystem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Governance platforms: ServiceNow GRC, Archer, or a custom SharePoint/Confluence space for decision logs"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Portfolio dashboards: Power BI, Tableau, or integrated ML platform dashboards (Weights & Biases, Azure ML)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Meeting management: standardized agenda templates in Outlook or Google Workspace with decision-tracker integrations"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Risk register tools: Microsoft Compliance Manager, Vanta, or enterprise GRC systems tied to audit workflows"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "RACI documentation: Lucidchart or Miro for decision-rights visualization and onboarding new members"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Comparison with alternatives"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Model"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
